        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s5" slide="5" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="5" environ="slide" chapter="1" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">Groups</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5"> group operation</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">multiplication</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">Associativity</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">associative</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">Existence of an Identity Element</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">identity element</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">Invertibility</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="5">inverse</keyword></keywords>
<xh:h2 xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">Groups</xh:h2>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="1" md5="33f6bdbad7007bdc1e5e1554f7582f65" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="5" item="1.1">
A group $G$ is a set equipped with a binary operation $*: G \times G \ra G$ (typically called <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"> group operation</xh:b> or "<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">multiplication</xh:b>"), such that:
<col_ul environment="col_ul" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_ul">
<col_li environment="col_ul" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:u xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ul"><xh:b environment="col_ul">Associativity</xh:b></xh:u>
\[(a* b)* c = a * (b * c),\]
for all $a, b, c \in G$. In other words, the group operation is <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ul">associative</xh:b>.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ul" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:u xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ul"><xh:b environment="col_ul">Existence of an Identity Element</xh:b></xh:u>
<newline environment="col_ul" chapter_type=""/>
There is an element $e \in G$, called an <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ul">identity element</xh:b>, such that:
\[g* e = e * g = g,\]
for all $g \in G$.
</col_li><col_li environment="col_ul" chapter_type="" wbtag="col_li">
<xh:u xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ul"><xh:b environment="col_ul">Invertibility</xh:b></xh:u>
<newline environment="col_ul" chapter_type=""/>
Each element $g \in G$ has an <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="col_ul">inverse</xh:b> $g^{-1} \in G$, such that:
\[g^{-1}* g = g* g^{-1} = e.\]
</col_li></col_ul>
</statement>
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:ul xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
  <xh:li environment="newcol">
Note that we do not require that $a* b = b * a$.
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="newcol">
We often write $ab$ to denote $a* b$.
  </xh:li>
</xh:ul>
</newcol></slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s6" slide="6" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="6" environ="slide" chapter="1" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="1" slide="6">commutative</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="6">abelian group</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="2" md5="a85844d4d7ece98fd846fbc30d376bde" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="6" item="1.2">
If $ab = ba$ for all $a, b \in G$. We say that the group operation is
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">commutative</xh:b>, and that $G$ is an <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">abelian group</xh:b>.
</statement>
<!-- For a field $k$, let $k^\times$ denote $k \bs \{0\} = \{s \in k\; |\; s \neq 0\}$. -->
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="3" md5="c5805b4d4e994ef881eee9f880299f69" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="6" item="1.3">
The following sets are groups, with respect to the specified group operations:
<xh:ul xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">
  <xh:li environment="statement">
$G = \mathbb{Q} \backslash \{0\}$, where the group operation is the usual multiplication for rational numbers.
The identity is $e = 1$, and the inverse of $a \in \mathbb{Q}\backslash\{0\}$ is $a^{-1} = \frac{1}{a}$.
The group $G$ is abelian.
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="statement">
$G = \mathbb{Q}$, where the group operation is the usual addition $+$ for rational numbers. The identity is $e = 0$.
The inverse of $a \in \mathbb{Q}$ with respect to $+$ is $-a$.
Note that $\mathbb{Q}$ is <xh:em environment="statement">NOT</xh:em> a group with respect to multiplication. For in that case, we have $e = 1$, but $0 \in \mathbb{Q}$ has no inverse
$0^{-1} \in \mathbb{Q}$ such that $0\cdot 0^{-1} = 1$.
  </xh:li>
</xh:ul>
<newline environment="statement" chapter_type=""/>
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"/>
</statement>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s7" slide="7" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="7" environ="slide" chapter="1" course="Math 2070"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="4" md5="09d2e3cedd374ec7fe8c13967134ab31" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="7" item="1.4">
Verify that the following sets are groups under the specified binary operation:
<xh:ul xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">
  <xh:li environment="statement">
$(\mathbb{Z}, +)$
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="statement">
$(\mathbb{R}, +)$
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="statement">
$(\mathbb{R}^\times, \cdot)$
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="statement">
$(U_m, \cdot)$, where $m \in \mathbb{N}$,
\[U_m = \{1, \xi_m, \xi_m^2, \ldots, \xi_m^{m - 1}\},\]
and
$\xi_m = e^{2\pi i/m} = \cos(2\pi/m) + i\sin(2\pi/m) \in \mathbb{C}$.
<!-- $(\mathbb{Z}_m, +)$, $m \in \mathbb{N}$. -->
<!--
@html_li
$(\mathbb{Z}_p^\times, \cdot)$, $p$ a prime number.
-->
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="statement">
The set of bijective functions $f: \mathbb{R} \ra \mathbb{R}$,
where $f * g:= f \circ g$ (i.e. composition of functions).
  </xh:li>
</xh:ul>
<newline environment="statement" chapter_type=""/>
