        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s9" slide="9" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="9" environ="slide" chapter="1" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="1" slide="9">Special Linear Group</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="6" md5="9b8c588cd35ab068fc000af50f88c20a" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="9" item="1.6">
The set $G = {\rm GL}(2, \mathbb{R})$
of real $2 \times 2$ matrices with nonzero determinants is a group
under matrix multiplication, with identity element:
\[e = \left(\begin{matrix} 1 &amp;amp; 0\\0&amp;amp; 1\end{matrix}\right).\]
In the group $G$, we have:
\[\left(\begin{matrix} a &amp;amp; b \\ c &amp;amp; d\end{matrix}\right)^{-1}
=
\frac{1}{ad - bc}\left(\begin{matrix}d &amp;amp; -b \\-c &amp;amp; a\end{matrix}\right)\]
<!--
%% The right&#45;hand side is well&#45;defined because a matrix
%% $g = \left(\begin{matrix} a &amp;amp; b \\ c &amp;amp; d\end{matrix}\right)$ with real coefficients
%% is invertible if and only if $\det g := ad &#45; bc \neq 0$.
-->
Note that there are matrices $A, B \in {\rm GL}(2, \mathbb{R})$
such that $AB \neq BA$. Hence ${\rm GL}(2, \mathbb{R})$ is not abelian.
<newline environment="statement" chapter_type=""/>
<xh:hr xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement"/>
<!--
In general, for $n \in \mathbb{N}$, $k$ a field,
the set ${\rm GL}(n, k)$ (<b>General Linear Group</b>) of $n \times n$ matrices $M$ with coefficients in $k$,
such that $\det M \neq 0$, is a group under matrix multiplication.
-->
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Exercise" wbtag="ex" num="7" md5="52399932d7161bf7c81711e389d19c86" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="9" item="1.7">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
The set ${\rm SL}(2, \mathbb{R})$ (<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">Special Linear Group</xh:b>)
of real $2 \times 2$ matrices with determinant $1$ is a group under matrix multiplication.
</newcol></statement>
