        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s10" slide="10" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="10" environ="slide" chapter="1" course="Math 2070"/>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="8" md5="f3b81ac27835303554e848ba93cffad2" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="10" item="1.8">
The identity element $e$ of a group $G$ is unique.
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="37f4b6dee2ffc6672031deec79665b0b">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Suppose there is an element $e' \in G$ such that $e' g = ge' = g$ for all $g \in G$.
Then, in particular, we have:
\[e'e = e\]
But since $e$ is an identity element, we also have $e'e = e'$. Hence, $e' = e$.
</newcol></substatement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="9" md5="1851fd3bfd53ed9ae77cee1d737d8118" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="10" item="1.9">
Let $G$ be a group.
For all $g \in G$, its inverse $g^{-1}$ is unique.
</statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="359cd7840f79f528524785a246a37f24">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Suppose there exists $g' \in G$ such that $g'g = gg' = e$.
By the associativity of the group operation, we have:
\[g' = g'e = g'(g g^{-1}) = (g'g)g^{-1} = e g^{-1} = g^{-1}.\]
Hence, $g^{-1}$ is unique.
</newcol></substatement>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s11" slide="11" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="11" environ="slide" chapter="1" course="Math 2070"/>
Let $G$ be a group with identity element $e$.
For $g \in G$, $n \in \mathbb{N}$,
let:
\[\begin{split}
g^n &amp;amp;:= \underbrace{g \cdot g \cdots g}_{n\text{ times}}.\\
g^{-n} &amp;amp;:= \underbrace{g^{-1} \cdot g^{-1} \cdots g^{-1}}_{n\text{ times}}\\
g^0 &amp;amp;:= e.
\end{split}\]
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="10" md5="413dfe67c18ba505d3b2256c719f3a8d" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="11" item="1.10">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Let $G$ be a group.
<xh:ol xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
  <xh:li environment="newcol">
For all $g \in G$,
we have:
\[(g^{-1})^{-1} = g.\]
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="newcol">
For all $a, b \in G$,
we have:
\[(ab)^{-1} = b^{-1}a^{-1}.\]
  </xh:li>
  <xh:li environment="newcol">
For all $g \in G$, $n, m \in \mathbb{Z}$, we have:
\[g^n\cdot g^m = g^{n + m}.\]
  </xh:li>
</xh:ol>
</newcol></statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="ef8fb97d271d5d2e855498ac9a9b41b7">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
<xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">Exercise.</xh:b>
</newcol></substatement>
</slide>
        <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" id="s12" slide="12" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" section="" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title=""><keywords slide="12" environ="slide" chapter="1" course="Math 2070"><keyword chapter="1" slide="12">order</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="12">order</keyword><keyword chapter="1" slide="12">infinite order</keyword></keywords>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="11" md5="a0591fc42ee4f89ab83102e9dc7e5e30" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="12" item="1.11">
Let $G$ be a group, with identity element $e$.
The <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">order</xh:b> of $G$ is the number of elements in $G$.
The <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">order</xh:b> $\ord g$ of an  $g \in G$
is the smallest $n \in \mathbb{N}$ such that $g^n = e$.
If no such $n$ exists, we say that $g$ has <xh:b xmlns:xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">infinite order</xh:b>.
</statement>
<statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Theorem" wbtag="thm" num="12" md5="e96b6aa05fb1d6c99e4e9e869060a697" course="Math 2070" chapter="1" slide="12" item="1.12">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Let $G$ be a group with identity element $e$.
Let $g$ be an element of $G$. If $g^n = e$ for some $n \in \mathbb{N}$,
then $\ord g$ divides $n$.
</newcol></statement>
<substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="723807213862930cca60acb6037d74ca">
<newcol environment="newcol" chapter_type="" wbtag="newcol">
Shown in class.
</newcol></substatement>
